\[f_n(x) = |f_{n - 1}(x)| - 1 = k - 1.\]This means if $f_0(x) = \pm k,$ then $f_k(x) = 0.$

Furthermore, if $f_n(x) = 0,$ then $f_{n + 1}(x) = -1,$ and $f_{n + 2}(x) = 0.$  Hence, $f_{100}(x) = 0$ if and only if $f_0(x) = 2k$ for some integer $k,$ $-50 \le k \le 50.$

